ght/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe essays in The Question of Peace in Modern Political Thought address the contribution that political theories of modern political philosophers have made to our understandings of peace. The discipline of peace research has reached a critical impasse, where the ideas of both “realist peace” and “democratic peace” are challenged by contemporary world events. Can we stand by while dictators violate the human rights of citizens? Can we impose a democratic peace through the projection of war? By looking back at the great works of political philosophy, this collection hopes to revive peace as an active question for political philosophy while making an original contribution to contemporary peace research and international relations.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aPeace (Philosophy). 0aPolitical sciencexPhilosophy. 4aPhilosophy. 4aPolitical Science. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Peace.2bisacsh1 aBagley, Paul, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBlitz, Mark, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBorman, David A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBradshaw, Leah, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCarty, Jarrett A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEnns, Diane, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGittings, John, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHolland, Ben, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHuber, Pamela, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJohnson, Laurie M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKoivukoski, Toivo, econtributor.4ctb4https://id